The question is pretty straightforward. Find $$\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=n}^{5n}{k-1\choose n-1}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^{n}\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^{k-n}$$ Attempt Let's denote $F$ as $$
\begin{align*}
& \lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=n}^{5n}{k-1 \choose n-1}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^{n}\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^{k-n} = \\ 
&= \lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^{n}\frac{1}{(n-1)!}\sum_{k=n}^{5n}\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^{k-n}\frac{(k-1)!}{(k-n)!} =  \\ &= \lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^{n}\frac{1}{(n-1)!}\sum_{k=0}^{4n}\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^{k}\frac{(k+n-1)!}{k!} = F
\end{align*}
$$ Try to establish a lower and upper bounds of denoted function $F$ , lower bound set to 0, and upper bound to $$\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^{n}\frac{1}{(n-1)!}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^{k}\frac{(k+n-1)!}{k!}$$ The sum inside of a limit equals to $(1 + \frac{4}{5})^{n}$ (by using Taylor series). By substituting this into the obtained upper bound, we're getting $0$ as an answer.

